<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-336-217  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 336 217.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Feb 5 1990 v36 n1795 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Charges AF re-bid could aid GD.(Air Force Strategic Air Commandcomputer network bid on by General Dynamics Corp.)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>General Dynamics Corp (GD), which underbid its nearest competitorby more than $400 million on construction of an Air ForceStrategic Air Command computer network, may be able to raise itsbid price because of an investigation into the original contract.andO;GD requested permission to switch to optical storage subsystemsfrom Japan to correct a mistake it made in its initial bid.andP;  Theoriginal bid, which proposed the use of US-made optical disk drivestorage systems, assumed the subsystems had twice the capacitythey actually had.andP;  Federal Data Systems, which bid $574 millionon the job, filed a complaint with the US General AccountingOffice, which ruled in Federal Data's favor.andP;  The contract must bere-bid.andP;  If GD adds $400 million to its original bid of $165million, it will still be well below Federal Data's bid.andP;  ScienceApplications International Corp is expected to be a third bidder.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Dynamics Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    GD.andO;Topic:     United States. Air ForceUnited States. General Accounting OfficeNetworksGovernment ContractsDefense ContractsContractsCompetitive Bidding.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>